<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910328-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>910328-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Meritor Savings Bank:   Bondholder Group Rejects   Concern's Tender for Notes</HL><DATE>03/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   MTOR</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)</IN><LP>   A group of Meritor Savings Bank bondholders rejected thePhiladelphia bank's proposed tender offer for a $115 millionnote issue, and brought suit seeking payment of $6.9 millioninterest on the issue.   Wilbur Ross, senior managing director at securitiesconcern Rothschild Inc., which represents the bondholders,said the bondholder group, which holds about half of the debtissue, objects to the steep discount at which Meritor isproposing to buy back the debt. Nonetheless, he added, &quot;welike what the bank is doing; it is getting itself into verygood shape.&quot; He said bondholders were willing to exchangesome of the debt for convertible preferred stock, which wouldbe counted as capital.</LP><TEXT>   Meritor recently offered to pay $240 for each $1,000principal amount of outstanding 12% capital notes, a move itsaid would increase the bank's capital by $89 million if allnotes were repurchased. The offer, subject to at least 90%being tendered, expires today.   Roger Hillas, chairman of Meritor, said the notes had beenselling between $160 and $200 when the offer was made. &quot;Wedon't understand how the price escalates from $200 to wherehe (Mr. Ross) thinks it is worth,&quot; he said.   He added that &quot;the important thing is that we are meetingall our obligations to everybody -- depositors, all othercreditors. This is a single offer to buy something.&quot; He addedthat Meritor &quot;absolutely&quot; is able to pay the interest ifrequired to do so.</TEXT></DOC>